:: Background {"position":"1200,725","size":"100,100"}
The Convention Concerning the Protection of the World Cultural and Natural Heritage, officially known as the World Heritage Convention, is a significant international agreement ratified by UNESCO (the United Nations Educational, Scientific, and Cultural Organization) in 1972. This Convention aims to identify, defend, and preserve cultural and natural places with exceptional universal significance. Recognizing these particular sites' importance in heritage, biodiversity, culture, and history, the Convention aims to protect them for current and future generations via international cooperation. International collaboration is required for the conservation and sustainable management of sites declared as World Heritage, as these sites are considered to have great universal importance. The Globe Heritage Convention is proof of the dedication of people all around the globe to protecting the most valuable natural and cultural treasures for future generations.

